no-unsafe-unknown

Warns when `unknown` is used in function parameter types or type assertions.

Source: custom rule for lintcn
Severity: warn (does not block CI)

The Problem

Agents often reach for `unknown` when they hit TypeScript friction instead of
reading the real types. In function arguments, that usually means the code is
giving up on the contract the function should actually enforce. In assertions,
it usually means the code is trying to force a conversion the type system does
not support.

What Gets Flagged

  function run(input: unknown) {}
  const fn = (input: Promise<unknown>) => input
  const value = input as unknown
  const result = (value as unknown) as Target

What The Warning Tells The Agent

  - For function parameters: read the real dependency and value types, then use
    the correct parameter type instead of routing everything through `unknown`
  - For assertions: stop forcing the conversion, read the actual source and
    target types, then narrow or transform the value properly

What Is Not Flagged

  - `unknown` outside function parameter types and assertions
  - ordinary typed parameters
  - assertions that do not involve `unknown`
  - `as const`

Preferred Alternatives

  // Instead of this
  function run(input: unknown) {}

  // Read the real contract and type it directly
  function run(input: RequestContext) {}

  // Instead of this
  const result = value as unknown as User

  // Narrow or validate first
  if (isUser(value)) {
    const result = value
  }
